TL;DR Version: 

Scale your goals down in the tough time and scale them up in the good time.  Escape the zone of Procrastination and Stay in the zone of Action.

---

There is a lot been said about goal-setting in personal development and self-help books. Some argue you should set high goals, "Aim for the Moon", "10X of what you think is achievable" they urge. While others suggesting set small, incremental goals that build up momentum.

How to reconcile this contradiction? I think the missing dimension is our state: what kind of goals are helpful and useful depends on how we are at that moment. 

I call this framework: **Scaleable Goal-Setting**.

![Scaleable Goal-Setting.jpg](data:image/png;base64,)
There are lows and highs throughout our days. Of course, we all want to ride high in life, feeling good and confident; but there are also times of set back, bad luck, or simply don't want to do anything. 

Procrastination happens in two situations: When when are in a low state, feeling defeated, even depressed, high goals like writing a book, getting in shape, or getting out of debt, seems unachievable. So we feel powerless so we don't even try to start. 
Also, when things do go well, but we only have small goals, like paying the bills, or doing the choirs, we often feel uninspired, aloof and question if we are not living up to our potential. In this framework, I call it the **Zone of Procrastination** and it is caused by a mismatch between goals and mental states. 

The opposite is the **Zone of Action**. When you are feeling down, set minimal goals. When I was depressed, I call getting out of bed a win. The next goal might be to take a shower. When you don't feel do anything and the grand goal seems overwhelming, start small, really small. Action fuels more action. When you feel good, set goals high, and even deliberately choose something you are likely to fail, because that is where the most growth happens.

One word of caution is the micro goals and the grand goals have to be aligned. (Hence the name scale, like scaling vectors) For example, a grand goal might be to become a best-selling author. Then, an aligned might be to write your first book. The micro goal to deploy, when you really don't feel like writing, merely write one page. 

I enjoy coming up with mental frameworks. If you enjoy this article, please consider giving it a like and sharing it.
